      <NewsComponent>
        <ContentItem>
          <MediaType FormalName="Text"/>
          <Format FormalName="bcNITF2.5"/>
          <DataContent>
            <media media-type="image" style="leftSide">
<media-reference mime-type="" data-location="#photo0" />
</media>
<p>Just hours after accepting the Democratic presidential nomination, John Kerry will hit the campaign trail running on Friday, launching a gruelling coast-to-coast tour to push home his bid for the White House.</p>

            <p>Seeking to build on the momentum created by the party's national convention in Boston, Kerry and vice presidential running mate John Edwards will hold a rally here Friday morning, before setting off on a 5,600-kilometer (3,500-mile) journey across the country.</p>
            <p>Following a rare and relatively unchallenged week in the national spotlight, the Kerry-Edwards ticket will once again be competing with the full force of the Republican re-election machine, as President George W. Bush prepares an aggressive return to his campaign.</p>
            <p>The Democrats devoted much of their convention to bashing the Bush administration over every issue from education and health care to Iraq and the war on terror.</p>
            <media media-type="image" style="rightSide">
<media-reference mime-type="" data-location="#photo1" />
</media>
<p>Kerry's campaign team compared their latest push to Harry Truman's 1948 "whistle-stop" campaign, when the embattled president saw off a strong challenge from Republican challenger Thomas Dewey by travelling thousands of kilometers (miles) by train and taking his program directly to the American people.</p>

            <p>The tour "will trace America's Westward expansion, highlighting the optimistic American spirit that is at the heart of the Kerry-Edwards plan to build a stronger America," said Kerry spokeswoman Allison Dobson.</p>
            <p>The newly appointed Democratic nominees plan to cover a combined total of 21 states.</p>
            <p>Bush, who spent the week on his Texas ranch, returns to the White House ahead of a punishing 48-hour campaign swing through the key battleground states of Missouri, Michigan, Ohio, and Pennsylvania.</p>
          </DataContent>
        </ContentItem>
